This decision-making policy is consistent with Bayesian reasoning. A Bayesian observer should respond “S2” whenever S2 has the greater posterior probability, i.e. whenever \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{p(\mathrm{S2}|x) }{p(\mathrm{S1}|x)}>1$$\end{document}p(S2|x)p(S1|x)>1, and respond “S1” otherwise. Using Bayes’ rule, this ratio of posterior probabilities can be expressed as the Bayes factor, i.e. \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{p(\mathrm{S2}|x) }{p(\mathrm{S1}|x)}=\frac{p(x|\mathrm{S2})p(\mathrm{S2}) }{p(x|\mathrm{S1})p(\mathrm{S1})}$$\end{document}p(S2|x)p(S1|x)=p(x|S2)p(S2)p(x|S1)p(S1). Substituting the Bayes factor into the inequality \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
