Thus, provided that the observer sets the type 1 criterion optimally, i.e. so as to maximize type 1 accuracy, the observer maximizes type 2 accuracy by always reporting high confidence. If the observer sets the type 1 criterion suboptimally (e.g. by setting c1 = -1 when p(S1) = p(S2) as in Figure 4A), then type 2 accuracy is maximized by reporting low confidence only for evidence samples that fall between the optimal and actual type 1 criterion (e.g. evidence samples between the optimal \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
